===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|p}} – a boat.

Later sometimes written as {{zh-l|*月}}, {{zh-l|*肉}} or {{zh-l|*凡}} in components.

===Etymology===
According to {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}}, a loan from {{der|zh|mkh-pro|*ɗuuk|*ɗuuk ~ *ɗuk|boat, canoe}}, whence {{cog|km|ទូក}} and {{cog|vi|nốc}} (< {{cog|mkh-vie-pro|*ɗoːk||boat}}). Foreign closed syllables having a long main vowel often correspond to open syllables in Old Chinese.

Possibly cognate of {{och-l|輈|trunk, pole}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

Yang Xiong's ''{{w|Fangyan (book)|Fangyan}}'' says that Old Chinese {{och-l|舟}} is common in central and eastern China, while its synonym {{och-l|船}} is used in western China.

